A 16-YEAR-OLD boy, implicated in the murder of a Joza girl in December, will return to the Grahamstown Magistrate s Court today to formally apply for bail.The 16 year old and his two co accused were arrested after the girl, reportedly around 15, was found dead on a dumpsite near a Joza High School.The police said she had stab wounds to her upper body. Tomorrow, the Johannesburg specialised commercial crimes court will hear the case of five suspects who were arrested for fraud and theft of petrol estimated at a value of R5m.Sandile Sikhosana, 46, a franchisee at Engen Tembisa Convenience Centre, and his daughter Nompumelelo, 27, who are executives at Engen Langlaagte Depot, allegedly created false fuel order forms to sell on the black market for personal gain.Truck drivers Lucky Sikhosana, 46, Jackson Motlhowa, 51, and Zwelibanzi Sibeko, 46, assisted with loading fuel into delivery trucks and transported it to service stations around Gauteng, including Engen Tembisa Convenience Centre from 2012 to 2014.The case against Nelson Mandela s grandson, Mbuso, will be heard tomorrow in the Johannesburg Family Court after he was arrested for failing to pay child support. Gugu Keswa has a three-yearold daughter with Mandela and said all she wants is for him to support his child. Reports suggested that Mbuso inherited R4m from his grandfather s estate but failed to support his daughter.Two suspects arrested for being in possession of stolen money will appear in the Bloemfontein Magistrate s Court. Police spokesperson Captain Philani Nkwalase said Baig Mahomed, 25, and Mahomed Hoosen, 50, were charged with possession of suspected stolen money or the proceeds of crime in connection with a total of R21.1m recovered at Bloemfontein Airport on Tuesday.The case against one of two accused in the Sakhumzi Restaurant murder will be heard in the Orlando Magistrate s Court on Wednesday. Njabulo Ngubane, 24 from Dube Hostel in Soweto was arrested in KwaZulu-Natal and is charged with murder and robbery with aggravating circumstances.The second accused, who cannot be named until he appears in court, was implicated in another restaurant robbery last November. He was also arrested in KwaZulu-Natal. On Thursday, a woman and her lover will appear in the Moretele Magistrate s Court in Hammanskraal for allegedly killing her husband and burying him in the bush.Fikile Mongwe, 36, and Innocent Pilosa, 21, are charged with murdering Selaelo Lekalakala, a government employee who was set to retire this year. On Friday, two suspects charged of trafficking persons will appear in the Danielskuil Magistrate s Court.Two minors, aged 15 and 16, were lured into visiting their friend in Postmasburg from Kimberley on January 9. Upon arrival, they were forced into prostitution by night and were locked up during the day.NONDUMISO ZWANE